    <a title="☮Karen" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1076079-karen"><img alt="☮Karen" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1643848766p2/1076079.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/211210410?book_show_action=true">Nov 14, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="☮Karen" class="user" itemprop="url" name="☮Karen" href="/user/show/1076079-karen">☮Karen</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1076079-karen?shelf=book-club">book-club</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1076079-karen?shelf=read-in-2016">read-in-2016</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer211210410" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8048524172248735320">*In person book club read #2.*<br/><br/>I liked this debut overall. I came off it feeling a message that family is there to help with the big life changing events, but when it comes to day to day survival, ya gotta have friends, as Bette Midler would say.<br/><br/>It is told from the perspective of Kimberly, fresh off the boat with her mother from Hong Kong, and placed by her aunt (evil woman) in a condemned NYC apartment with no heat but plenty of cockroaches and rats. Neither spoke much English, but Kimberly&apos;s sp</span>
  <span id="freeText8048524172248735320" style="display:none">*In person book club read #2.*<br /><br />I liked this debut overall. I came off it feeling a message that family is there to help with the big life changing events, but when it comes to day to day survival, ya gotta have friends, as Bette Midler would say.<br /><br />It is told from the perspective of Kimberly, fresh off the boat with her mother from Hong Kong, and placed by her aunt (evil woman) in a condemned NYC apartment with no heat but plenty of cockroaches and rats. Neither spoke much English, but Kimberly's spunk and ingenuity got them through time and time again. The level of their poverty and bad luck sort of broke my little heart. In the end, I felt a disconnect from the characters but thought it a nice enough story.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8048524172248735320" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


