    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3025807366" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3025807366" />
    <a title="Bam cooks the books ;-)" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5922426-bam-cooks-the-books--"><img alt="Bam cooks the books ;-)" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1559653145p2/5922426.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3025807366?book_show_action=true">Nov 04, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Bam cooks the books ;-)" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Bam cooks the books ;-)" href="/user/show/5922426-bam-cooks-the-books--">Bam cooks the books ;-)</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5922426-bam-cooks-the-books--?shelf=2019-reads">2019-reads</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5922426-bam-cooks-the-books--?shelf=historical-fiction">historical-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5922426-bam-cooks-the-books--?shelf=library-book">library-book</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5922426-bam-cooks-the-books--?shelf=2019-national-literary-festival-smc">2019-national-literary-festival-smc</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3025807366" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5027762211179393902">*3.5 stars rounded up. <br/><br/>**Jean Kwok is one of the authors who will be attending the National Literary Festival at St Mary&apos;s College, Notre Dame, IN on November 8 &amp; 9, 2019: <a target='_blank' rel='noopener nofollow' href='https://www.saintmarys.edu/LiteraryFestival'>https://www.saintmarys.edu/LiteraryFe...</a><br/><br/>I wanted to read at least one of Jean&apos;s books before attending the festival and chose this, her first book, which is about the Chinese immigrant experience. It reads almost like a memoir--in fact, it&apos;s often easy to forget that it is fiction. <br/><br/>The protagonist of the story is eleven-year-o</span>
  <span id="freeText5027762211179393902" style="display:none">*3.5 stars rounded up. <br /><br />**Jean Kwok is one of the authors who will be attending the National Literary Festival at St Mary's College, Notre Dame, IN on November 8 &amp; 9, 2019: <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="https://www.saintmarys.edu/LiteraryFestival">https://www.saintmarys.edu/LiteraryFe...</a><br /><br />I wanted to read at least one of Jean's books before attending the festival and chose this, her first book, which is about the Chinese immigrant experience. It reads almost like a memoir--in fact, it's often easy to forget that it is fiction. <br /><br />The protagonist of the story is eleven-year-old Kimberly Chang who emigrates from Hong Kong with her widowed mother. They are beholden to Kim's aunt and uncle who paid all their expenses and now employ them in their clothing sweatshop in Manhattan. The apartment they are given to live in is rat and bug infested and lacks heat, but Kim's mother won't rock the boat to protest and so they put up with many atrocities. This is the American Dream?<br /><br />Kim finds it difficult at first to understand the spoken language and customs but eventually her native intelligence shines forth and she is given some wonderful opportunities. Will she accept them or follow love instead?<br /><br />I thought this story very interesting, describing the immigrant experience and difficulties adjusting to a new life and customs, not to mention the language. Kim's early confusion with the spoken language is well illustrated in the book by putting the confused word in italics: for example, a schoolmate's mother says she is a {really state} agent. Idioms are also very difficult to comprehend for those struggling with ESL. Kim embarrasses herself and her male teacher by asking for 'a rubber' during a test and the class explodes in laughter. She has no clue what she has said incorrectly until another girl slips her an eraser and tells her the correct word. <br /><br />The story is told from Kimberly's first person pov, which can limit the depth of other characterizations. For instance, I never really understood the aunt's motivations for her harsh treatment of her sister and niece. I also found it curious that, though the Chang's shopped and worshipped in Chinatown, they never sought out friendships there or the support of other immigrants. <br /><br />I'm looking forward to meeting this author and others on Saturday! I will add more to my review afterwards.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5027762211179393902" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


